----------------------------------------------------
The Principal AI/ML Engineer provides technical leadership for AI engineering across the full development lifecycle. The role owns architecture, standards, and delivery for multimodal and large language model (LLM) based systems, ensuring strong governance, safety, and reliability within a production healthcare environment. The position involves advanced, specialized work in machine learning, natural language processing, generative AI, biomedical informatics standards, cloud infrastructure, and MLOps.

----------------------------------------------------
JOB DUTIES
----------------------------------------------------
1. Owns end-to-end AI system design, from data and feature engineering through model training, deployment, and monitoring.

2. Owns architecture, standards, and delivery for multimodal and LLM-based systems, ensuring strong governance, safety, and reliability.

3. Designs and operates multimodal and LLM-based systems, including retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) and knowledge operations, covering vector databases, chunking and embedding strategies, hybrid dense and lexical retrieval, grounding, citation and freshness controls, de-duplication, policy-aware queries, and audit-ready traces.

4. Implements human-in-the-loop controls to meet safety, quality, and regulatory requirements, including structured prompts, guardrails, output validation, and human checkpoints for high-risk actions.

5. Governs data quality, lineage, and compliance across batch, streaming, and analytics platforms, including oversight of data usage, consent, and compliance at scale.

6. Establishes continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD) practices for machine learning, including model registries, automated retraining, rollback strategies, and incident playbooks, and implements progressive delivery through canary and blue-green releases.

7. Applies site reliability engineering (SRE) practices to AI systems through service-level objectives (SLOs), error budgets, and release discipline, including observability across retrieval and generation, model and feature drift detection, calibration, bias monitoring, user feedback loops, and degradation policies.

8. Implements zero-trust security controls for AI services, delivering policy-aware outputs and full auditability through scoped IAM, encryption, tokenization, masking, safety filters, jailbreak defenses, content moderation, model cards, audit trails, and retention policies.

9. Designs and implements agentic AI systems, including assistive, semi-autonomous, and autonomous agent patterns with clearly defined approval boundaries; planner, executor, retrieval, memory, policy, and evaluator agents; multi-agent topologies such as manager-worker, mediator, and reflective patterns; and secure agent-to-agent interoperability with defined schemas, access controls, and attestations.

10. Optimizes inference and serving infrastructure, including parameter-efficient model tuning (LoRA and QLoRA), distillation and quantization, GPU and TPU scheduling, throughput optimization, and cost and performance controls such as token budgeting and caching.

11. Engineers large-scale data processing and orchestration pipelines across data lakes, data warehouses, and streaming platforms, incorporating schema evolution and data contracts.

12. Leads architecture reviews, defines engineering standards, publishes reference implementations, and mentors senior engineers and data scientists.

13. Translates business objectives into prompts, retrieval schemas, experiments, and measurable outcomes, with ownership of evaluation, guardrails, and business impact.

14. Drives adoption of AI solutions through documentation, demonstrations, and reusable patterns, and communicates complex technical concepts to non-technical and clinical stakeholders.

